CHOLERA ADVISORY - PACIFIC ISLANDS (03)
***************************************
A ProMED post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
Cholera advisory - Pacific Islands (posted 15 Sep 1999)
Cholera advisory - Pacific Islands (02) (posted 17 Sep 1999)
Cholera, imported - New Zealand 990130225224
Cholera, imported - New Zealand (02) 990821212906
Cholera, imported - New Zealand (03) 990827102657
Date: Tue, 21 Sep 1999 14:29:05 +1200
From: Baker, Michael <Michael.Baker@esr.cri.nz>

I am replying to the ProMED posting of 15 Sep 1999 [cited above. This
posting implied some difficulty in obtaining information on the travel
destinations of two New Zealanders who had developed cholera after
returning from holiday in the Pacific. I am not sure where this apparent
information block has come from. New Zealand is
committed to free exchange of surveillance information on emerging public
health hazards. Imported cholera cases are fully reported in New Zealand
along with their travel history. This information is disseminated here in
a variety of forms, including the New Zealand Public Health Report (NZPHR),
which is sent monthly to most medical practitioners and public health
workers in NZ. This journal is also distributed internationally and posted
on the NZ Ministry of Health's web page
<http://www.moh.govt.nz/nzphr.html>.
The first of these two imported cases of cholera was reported in the March
issue of the NZPHR. This case was in a 28 year old man who developed
cholera in December 1998 after returning from a holiday in Fiji. The
second case was a 26 year old man who developed cholera in July, again
after returning from a holiday in Fiji. This case will be reported in the
September NZPHR.

Both cases were due to _Vibrio cholerae_ 01 biotype El Tor, subgroup Ogawa.

--
Michael Baker, Public Health Physician
ESR
Kenepuru Science Centre
PO Box 50 348 Porirua
Wellington, New Zealand
e-mail: michael.baker@esr.cri.nz
