[Since the report appeared in the WHO WER in September, we erroneously
assumed it referred to current cases. Now all is clear. They are the same
ones imported from Fiji in January & July which we had already reported
(see refs. above). It appears that both ProMED & WHO have reported them
twice. We note that the International Health Regulations require reporting
of all cholera cases to WHO within 24 hours; reporting them in a monthly
bulletin 2 months after the fact does not fulfill that requirement - Mod.JW
[Thanks to Dr. Baker for calling the information to our attention. In
fairness to those who did not find it on their own, I note that the New
Zealand Public Health Report as posted on the website does not include
specific reference to cholera in the Table of Contents. One has to read
the entire issue to find the single paragraph in the Surveillance Reports
section. I am unfamiliar with the other forms of information dissemination
used by the New Zealand public health officials in this case, but again I
guess we missed the reports. It is important that subscribers help us to
find such information. - Mod.ES
[It is also noteworthy that the 17 Sep 1999 posting cited above refers to
two cases of typhoid among cruise ship passengers. It is apparent that, if
the latter diagnosis is correct, it must represent a separate outbreak. -
Mods.JW/ES
......................................jw/es
